definition.value: Enables the directed movement of lactone from one side of a membrane to the other. A lactone is a cyclic ester of a hydroxy carboxylic acid, containing a 1-oxacycloalkan-2-one structure, or an analogue having unsaturation or heteroatoms replacing one or more carbon atoms of the ring.
Catalysis of the hydrolysis of (1--gt-4)-beta-D-glucosidic linkages in beta-D-glucans containing (1--gt-3) and (1--gt-4) bonds.
Catalysis of the hydrolysis of (1--gt-3)-beta-D-glucosidic linkages in (1--gt-3)-beta-D-glucans.
Interacting selectively and non-covalently with the retinoic acid receptor, a ligand-regulated transcription factor belonging to the nuclear receptor superfamily.
Interacting selectively and non-covalently with any of the peroxisome proliferator activated receptors, alpha, beta or gamma.
Upregulation of the activity of the enzyme ornithine decarboxylase.
Modulation of the activity of the enzyme ornithine decarboxylase.
Interacting selectively and non-covalently with X11-like protein, a neuron-specific adaptor protein.
A prolongation or process extending from a cell, e.g. a flagellum or axon.
A prolongation or process extending from a nerve cell, e.g. an axon or dendrite.
Interacting selectively and non-covalently with any protein or protein complex (a complex of two or more proteins that may include other nonprotein molecules) using energy from the hydrolysis of ATP.
Interacting selectively and non-covalently with the microtubule constituent protein alpha-tubulin.
Interacting selectively and non-covalently with the microtubule constituent protein gamma-tubulin.

A enzyme complex of which the core is a heterodimer composed of a light (alpha) and heavy (beta) chain, and requires several other water-soluble proteins of cytosolic origin for activity. Functions in superoxide generation by the NADPH-dependent reduction of O2.
Interacting selectively and non-covalently with any complex of RNA and protein.
Interacting selectively and non-covalently with any part of a ribosome.
Interacting selectively and non-covalently with any part of the larger ribosomal subunit.
Interacting selectively and non-covalently with any part of the small ribosomal subunit.
The portion of a neuron that includes the nucleus, but excludes cell projections such as axons and dendrites.

label.value: cysteine-type endopeptidase inhibitor activity involved in apoptotic process

definition.value: Stops, prevents or reduces the activity of a cysteine-type endopeptidase involved in the apoptotic process.

label.value: cysteine-type endopeptidase regulator activity involved in apoptotic process

definition.value: Modulates the activity of a cysteine-type endopeptidase involved in the apoptotic process.

A protein complex whose composition varies amongst species -  in rice it probably exists in a homo-tetramer to homo-hexamer form and in Gram-negative bacteria as a dimer. Functions in the hydrolysis of alpha-(1,6)-D-glucosidic branch linkages.
Regular periodic sub membranous arrays of vinculin in skeletal and cardiac muscle cells, these arrays link Z-discs to the sarcolemma and are associated with links to extracellular matrix.
Interacting selectively and non-covalently and stoichiometrically with a chromatin insulator sequence, a DNA sequence that prevents enhancer-mediated activation or repression of transcription.

Plant storage body for amylose and amylopectin, 1-100um in diameter. Also contains small amounts of enzymes, amino acids, lipids and nucleic acids. The shape of the grain varies widely amongst species, but is often spherical or disk-shaped.
Interacting selectively and non-covalently with single-stranded telomere-associated DNA.
The alignment of chromosomes at the metaphase plate, a plane halfway between the poles of the meiotic spindle, during meiosis I.
The alignment of chromosomes at the metaphase plate, a plane halfway between the poles of the meiotic spindle, during meiosis II.
The nucleus of a germ cell, a reproductive cell in multicellular organisms.
The nucleus of a megasporocyte, a diploid cell that undergoes meiosis to produce four megaspores, and its descendents.
Either of two nuclei located centrally in a flowering plant embryo sac that eventually fuse to form the endosperm nucleus.
The nucleus of an antipodal cell, one of three cells of the embryo sac in angiosperms, found at the chalazal end of the embryo away from the point of entry of the pollen tube, and its descendents.
The nucleus of a plant egg cell. This nucleus is found at the micropylar end of the embryo.
The narrow gap that separates the presynaptic and postsynaptic membranes, into which neurotransmitter is released.
A cytokinesis process that involves a set of conserved proteins including FtsZ, and results in the formation of two similarly sized and shaped cells.

label.value: rDNA spacer replication fork barrier binding

definition.value: Interacting selectively and non-covalently with replication fork barriers found in rDNA spacers, sites that inhibit replication forks in the direction opposite to rDNA transcription.
Any process that stops, prevents, or reduces the frequency, rate or extent of DNA replication by impeding the progress of the DNA replication fork.
Catalysis of the reaction -  NAD(+) + precorrin-2 -eq- 2 H(+) + NADH + sirohydrochlorin.
Interacting selectively and non-covalently with tumor necrosis factor, a proinflammatory cytokine produced by monocytes and macrophages.
Interacting selectively and non-covalently with a neurotrophin, any of a family of growth factors that prevent apoptosis in neurons and promote nerve growth.
Interacting selectively and non-covalently with the protein-tyrosine kinase receptor ErbB-3|HER3.
Interacting selectively and non-covalently with ubiquitin, a protein that when covalently bound to other cellular proteins marks them for proteolytic degradation.
Catalysis of the reaction -  5-phospho-alpha-D-ribose 1-diphosphate + H2O -eq- ribose 1,5 bisphosphate + phosphate + H+.
Catalysis of the reaction -  glycerol 3-phosphate + H2O -eq- glycerol + phosphate.

label.value: DNA replication, removal of RNA primer

definition.value: Removal of the Okazaki RNA primer from the lagging strand of replicating DNA, by a combination of the actions of DNA polymerase, DNA helicase and an endonuclease.
Catalysis of the unwinding of the DNA helix in the direction 3' to 5'.
Catalysis of the unwinding of the DNA helix in the direction 5' to 3'.
Catalysis of the reaction -  ATP + H2O -eq- ADP + phosphate -  drives the unwinding of the DNA helix in the direction 3' to 5'.
Catalysis of the reaction -  ATP + H2O -eq- ADP + phosphate -  drives the unwinding of the DNA helix in the direction 5' to 3'.
Catalysis of the reaction -  ATP + H2O -eq- ADP + phosphate -  this reaction requires the presence of single-stranded DNA, and it drives another reaction.
